Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Oliver Garcia¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Ford GoBike is the Bay Area's new bike share system, with thousands of public bikes for use across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. Our bike share is designed with convenience in mind; its a fun and affordable way to get around town. The data analyzed is from January, February and March of 2019 and was downloaded from https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/index.html

REMEMBER TO INSTALL geopandas (conda install geopandas), erlang (pip install python-erlang) and basemap (conda install basemap conda install basemap-data-hires)

Tidiness¶

  • There are no real tidiness issues but for my analysis is better to extract the day of the week and the hour from start_time. The analysis will have a time granularity of hours.
  • I will also add a column to specify if the day is weekday or weekend day and a column for holiday. It might be important to know which days are holydays as they might affect the behavior of the custumers
  • For the multivariate analysis I will have to round the start latitud to multiples of 0.002 degrees (in SF Bay area 0.002 degrees of latitud are equivalent to an 1/8 of mile) and round the start longitud to multiples of 0.0025 degrees (in SF Bay area 0.0025 degrees of longitud are equivalent to an 1/8 of mile), this is needed to create a grid on top of a map of San Francisco

Tidiness¶

Define¶

There are no real tidiness issues but for my analysis is better to extract the day of the week and the time from start time.

Code¶

In [17]:
# extracting date
fordgobike_clean['start_date']=fordgobike_clean['start_time'].dt.date
# extracting week day name
fordgobike_clean['week_day_name']=fordgobike_clean['start_time'].dt.day_name()
# adding flad for weekend day
fordgobike_clean['weekend']=fordgobike_clean['week_day_name'].apply(
    lambda weekday: True if weekday in ('Saturday','Sunday') else False)
# extracting time from start_time
fordgobike_clean['start_hour']=fordgobike_clean['start_time'].dt.hour
fordgobike_clean['duration_hour']=fordgobike_clean['duration_sec']/3600
In [18]:
# adding flag for holyday
USHoliday = USFederalHolidayCalendar().holidays(
        start=fordgobike_clean['start_time'].min(), end=fordgobike_clean['start_time'].max())
fordgobike_clean['is_holiday'] = fordgobike_clean['start_date'].astype('datetime64').isin(USHoliday)

Define¶

For the multivariate analysis I will have to round the start latitud to multiples of 0.002 degrees (in SF Bay area 0.002 degrees of latitud are equivalent to a 1/8 of mile) and round the start longitud to multiples of 0.0025 degrees (in SF Bay area 0.0025 degrees of longitud are equivalent to a 1/8 of mile), this is needed to create a grid on top of a map of San Francisco.

Code¶

In [20]:
fordgobike_clean['start_latitude_grid']=0.002*round(fordgobike_clean['start_station_latitude']/0.002,0)
fordgobike_clean['start_longitude_grid']=0.0025*round(fordgobike_clean['start_station_longitude']/0.0025,0)

Analysis¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains one record for each time a bike is used that specifies start time, end time and duration of the trip as well as start and end location of the trip. The data also provides basic information of the user like gender, year of birth, suscriber or casual costumer.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The location and user information can give insights of the demographic of the costumers where they are geographically, start and end time in conjuntion with location can show where and when are used more. The previous mentioned features can be used to position the bikes in the locations where they are most needed when they are more needed.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

All 3 basic features of the dataset which are trip duration, trip start time, trip start location and user information can support an interesting analysis of where the bikes should be placed and at what times.

Usually customer behavior for any service is different between weekends, weekdays and holidays, for this reason I will split the data in wekkend data and weekday data excluding holidays for this analysis¶

Bivariate Exploration¶

Number of users per hour (erlangs)¶

Using the erlang B formula (refer to this link for more information https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erlang_(unit)) but changing the number of channels for number of bikes we can estimate how many bikes are needed per hour to cover the user demand. The hour of maximum erlang will tell what is the total number of bikes needed to cover San Francisco (this data comes from San Francisco)

For this analysis I will define an erlang as 1 bike that has been used for 1 hour.

In [37]:
# Calculating erlangs per hour
# Weekdays
weekday_usage = fordgobike_weekday.groupby('start_hour',as_index=False)['duration_hour'].sum()
weekday_count = fordgobike_weekday['start_date'].nunique()
# the previous 2 lines calculate the total usage per hour of all week days but, 
# I am interested in the average usage per hour which is calculated in the next line
weekday_usage['duration_hour']=weekday_usage['duration_hour']/weekday_count

# Weekends
weekend_usage = fordgobike_weekend.groupby('start_hour',as_index=False)['duration_hour'].sum()
weekend_count = fordgobike_weekend['start_date'].nunique()
# the previous 2 lines calculate the total usage per hour of all weekend days but, 
# I am interested in the average usage per hour which is calculated in the next line
weekend_usage['duration_hour']=weekend_usage['duration_hour']/weekend_count
In [38]:
base_color = sb.color_palette()[2]
second_color = sb.color_palette()[3]
In [39]:
# Erlangsper hour during weekdays
plt.figure(figsize=(16,6));
sb.barplot(data=weekday_usage, x='start_hour', y='duration_hour', color = base_color);
busy_hour_erl = weekday_usage['duration_hour'].max()
# minimum required bikes during busy hour for 1% unavailability
min_required_bikes = erlang.extended_b_lines(busy_hour_erl, 0.001)
print(f'Busy hour erlangs = {busy_hour_erl}, busy hour minimum required bikes = {min_required_bikes}')

Busy hour erlangs = 178.71871863799373, busy hour minimum required bikes = 215
In [40]:
# Erlangsper hour during weekends
plt.figure(figsize=(16,6));
sb.barplot(data=weekend_usage, x='start_hour', y='duration_hour', color = base_color)
weekend_usage['duration_hour'].max()
Out[40]:
85.13250000000023

The charts above shows that the hour of highest usage is 5pm during weekdays with an average of 178.8 erlangs of use at that hour.

The erlang B formula (use this link https://www.erlang.com/calculator/erlb/) tells me that fordgobike needs 215 bikes to service a load of 178.8 Erlang with a probability that 1% of the user won't find a bike because all bikes are in use. In other words, fordgobike needs 215 bikes in the geographical area of interest to cover the demand.

The above result is based only on capacity and demand and doesn't consider how far is the bike from the customer. The multivariate analysis will dig deeper into capacity, demand and location.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Number of users per hour (erlangs) per location¶

This is a similar analysis than the bivariate analysis but I will focus on 8am and 5pm of weekdays because they are the hours of highest use. I will use the latitud and longitud to show the results in a map.

In [41]:
weekday_count = fordgobike_weekday['start_date'].nunique()
# Filtering for 8am weekdays
weekday_8am = fordgobike_weekday.query("start_hour == 8")
# Calculating the usage per location at 8am
weekday_8am_loc = weekday_8am.groupby(['start_hour','start_latitude_grid','start_longitude_grid'],
                                      as_index=False)['duration_hour'].sum()
# Calculating the average per day for 8am
weekday_8am_loc['duration_hour']=weekday_8am_loc['duration_hour']/weekday_count
# calculating minimum required bikes (at 1% unavailability) by location at 8am
weekday_8am_loc['min_required_bikes'] = weekday_8am_loc['duration_hour'].apply(
    lambda duration: erlang.extended_b_lines(duration, 0.001))



# Filtering for 5pm weekdays
weekday_5pm = fordgobike_weekday.query("start_hour == 17")
# Calculating the usage per location at 5pm
weekday_5pm_loc = weekday_5pm.groupby(['start_hour','start_latitude_grid','start_longitude_grid'],
                                      as_index=False)['duration_hour'].sum()
# Calculating the average per day for 5pm
weekday_5pm_loc['duration_hour']=weekday_5pm_loc['duration_hour']/weekday_count
# calculating minimum required bikes (at 1% unavailability) by location at 5pm
weekday_5pm_loc['min_required_bikes'] = weekday_5pm_loc['duration_hour'].apply(
    lambda duration: erlang.extended_b_lines(duration, 0.001))

The erlang B formula must roundup the results to the nearest integer because you cannot have 1.5 bikes in a given location. The roundup of the erlang B formula generates a new minimum required number of bikes during busy hour

In [43]:
min_required_bikes_8am = weekday_8am_loc['min_required_bikes'].sum()
print(f'Busy hour minimum required bikes considering geographical distribution of users at 5pm is {min_required_bikes_8am}')

In [44]:
min_required_bikes_5pm = weekday_5pm_loc['min_required_bikes'].sum()
print(f'Busy hour minimum required bikes considering geographical distribution of users at 5pm is {min_required_bikes_5pm}')

Busy hour minimum required bikes considering geographical distribution of users at 5pm is 1381
  • Fordgobike must consider the second results of 1381 bikes for the minimum required bikes as the valid number because this consider the geographical distribution of users an ensure that there will be an available bike near a potential user with a 99% probability.
  • The number of required bikes could be reduced if we reduce the availability probability (for example to 98%)

            llcrnrlon=-122.46,
            llcrnrlat=37.72,
            epsg = 4326)

# adding streets background image
m.arcgisimage(service='ESRI_StreetMap_World_2D', xpixels = 1000, verbose= False);

# adding grid with number of bikes required
m.scatter(lon,lat, latlon=True,c=bikes,s=100,marker='s',cmap='tab20b', alpha=0.7);

# adding color band legend
plt.colorbar(label=r'required bikes')
plt.clim(0, weekday_5pm_loc['min_required_bikes'].max())
  • The 8am and 5pm maps shows more concentration of user in the mission district and financial district of SF which are commercail districts. The maps shows less users in Oakland, Berkeley and residential areas.
  • The previously described distribution of users is more accentuated in the 5pm map.
  • It is not surprising that bikes are used more in commercial areas where car parking is limited.
  • The 8am and 5pm show how many bikes per squarequarter mile must be available so every potential user can find an idle bike no further than 100 yards away.
